<font color="#FF0000">THE WALL</font><br>
<tt>Wed Feb 25  6:08:58 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
This is on the last day of posts. I am sorry that I am missing you all. Thank you for giving me a chane to talk about the war.<br><br>
To those of you who are proud of being a Vet.. Right On!<br>
To those of us who are proud of being anti-war protesters,<br>
Right On too!<br><br>
I spent the last four days in D.C. and visited the Vietnam Memorial. Here is something I am writing, (in process) about that experience.<br><br>
I visited the wall.<br>
There were others there, with me<br>
who were also in their own world.<br>
People walking, standing, staring.<br><br>
Some touched the wall, caressing it<br>
across its face. Some touched a special<br>
name as though touching that name helped<br>
bring that person back to us... And it did.<br><br>
Some stopped at a special name and did a rubbing,<br>
to bring that part of the wall away with them. <br>
And they could.<br><br>
Some looked at the wall almost afraid to touch it,<br>
afraid that the connection would fill them with something<br>
too powerful to control. And they were right.<br><br>
I started walking and looking. <br>
Five names per row. <br>
One row on the first tile.<br>
Three rows, fifteen names on the next<br>
twnety five, thrity five ...<br>
Almost a thousand by the middle.<br><br>
Each name, unique. Each represented the<br>
potential for a life. He/she could have been <br>
here today but... <br><br>
In a sense they are here,for a monment.<br>
For everyone of us who  come or care. <br>
But also they are gone forever, lost. <br>
The loss of someone's brother, or son or father <br>
is overwhelming.<br>
The saddness of the loss of the thousands of fathers, <br>
brothers sons gripped me so . <br>
I felt a sadness a sorrow an aloneness that took me <br>
away to a quiet solitude that on one could touch.<br><br>
I took the hand of my wife, and looked at my children. <br>
Holding on to make sure that what I had was real and could<br>
not get away. I needed an anchor, something solid to help <br>
keep me together. As I cried freely for all that was lost.<br>
As I cried with all the parents and children, brothers and <br>
sisters who were ever there or who shared that pain. And it<br>
was a pain as real as any hurt I have ever received.<br><br>
The names...Morales, Johnson, Walters,<br>
Isenberg, Howard, Youngbear. <br>
I knew the Youngbear family when I lived<br>
in Minnesota, though not this warrior. <br><br>
When I started, I could see the land, and looked<br>
down upon the tiles. <br>
Now, in the middle all I could see are names on <br>
black marble. No sky, no horizon, only the names<br>
of those who passed. I felt trapped by the image,<br>
as though I was sinking with no way out but to continue.<br>
And so I did, I climbed out from that blackness, <br>
I then saw once again bits of sky and land.<br>
Finally, I made my way out, to see the world, <br>
to the saftey of 1998.<br><br>
At the foot of the marble were flowers, some wilted<br>
some new. A picture of a soldier in Vietnam. He was smiling.<br>
Behind the names was the cold blackness of the Marble.<br>
On th emarble were the muted reflections<br>
of those of us who have come to pay our respects.<br>
Our details were not clear, <br>
the tears on our cheeks were not visible, but no one<br>
there needed to see the tears to know of their presence.<br><br>
Thank you all for walking with me through this site. I have learned from it.
<p><code>-- jproujan@k12s.phast.umass.edu  (Jed Proujansky) </code><p>


